postcontent:
The Stainless Steel Mil-Spec is built on a full-size frame and slide. The pistol is made from stainless steel, which has a polished finish on the flat surfaces and bead-blasted matte finish on the rounded areas. The 5 inch barrel is match grade and made from stainless steel. The slide features slanted serrations on the rear only. title: For Sale/Trade:  Russian Arms Collection
postcontent:
I have a collection of Russian arms for sale. I am selling these guns together as a single lot for $800. I would alternatively sell everything but the M1895 revolver for $650.

The Breakdown:

(Top)

All matching 1938 Tula Arsenal M91/30 Mosin Nagant imported by CAI, unfired, still in the cosmoline. This gun was specially hand picked out of a lot and is of above average fit and finish. Includes bayonet, sling, mag pouches, cleaning and tool kit and two packages of collectible 7.62 x 54R wrapped in paper and twine (warning, corrosive!).

(Middle) 

Pre-ban 1979 dated Chinese Type 56 Simonov Carbine (SKS), marked as being made at factory 366. Not a Russian SKS, but this particular gun is actually made better. It was made to the same specs as the Chinese Security Forces guns intended for the state run private police force. As such, it is one of the highest quality and finest SKS variants ever made. It was imported by Keng's Firearm Specialties before importation of Chinese arms was banned. Keng's imported mostly Chinese Security Forces guns but this one isn't marked with the Security Forces mark which is odd. What I do know is that it is NOT a Norinco. Who knows what group sold it to Keng's or if it was officially sanctioned by the Chinese Goverment or sold to the US market out the back door. One never knows with the Chicoms. It was imported at a time when it was still a practically brand new gun. The gun is all matching except for the 10 round fixed magazine. Importer information is discreetly and professionally engraved (as opposed to crudely electropenciled) under the barrel below the gas tube and is hidden by the cleaning rod and bayonet so you don't see it unless you know where to look, (unlike most other SKS carbines). Includes sling, spike-type bayonet, mag pouches, 30 round detachable mag, 100 rounds of 7.62 x 39 on 10 round stripper clips, a spare 20 round box 7.62 x 39 and cleaning kit (stored inside stock). 

(Bottom)

1944 Izhevsk arsenal M1895 Nagant gas-seal revolver in un-issued condition imported by PW Arms. Includes holster, lanyard, two cleaning rods, one screwdriver tool and a 50 round box of 7.62 Nagant gas seal ammunition.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P220 45 ACP
postcontent:
Sig Sauer P220 45 ACP

Still the one to beat If you’re looking for a definition of SIG SAUER®’s well-known unfailing reliability, look at the P220®. This is the pistol that can fire off 10,000 rounds in a day, without a single failure. It is the one that earned the trust of professionals who demanded a .45ACP that would always come through when the stakes were high.

The P220 operates by the locked breech short-recoil method pioneered John Browning. On firing, the slide and barrel are locked together until, after a few millimeters of rearward movement, the barrel is cammed down at the rear after the pressure has dropped enough when the bullet has departed the barrel, whereupon the slide completes the rearward stroke ejecting the spent cartridge. The recoil spring then propels the slide forwards, stripping a round from the magazine, and in the last few millimeters of forward movement, the barrel is cammed upwards at the rear, locking the slide and barrel together again. I

Folks this is one of my go to pistols.  I have not shot it a lot, but I don’t need to practice with this one.  What I see is what I can hit on the range.  

It comes with two mags and 100 rounds of 45 ACP.

I am asking $875 for this weapon.

As those who have dealt with me before can attest, no reasonable offer will be refused, but in this case I will  not come off this price too much.  It is, after all a Sig Sauer.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1911 commander and circuit judge
postcontent:
OK guys settle down. I didn't take the time to post these guns to give them away. If your looking for the deal of the century just click on the next ad now. You won't like me very much if you offer some dumb shit price or trade offer. I'm really only looking to sell at a fair price to someone who will appreciate these firearms for their own pleasure, not see them posted next week for twice what I sold them for. If I wanted that I'd be at the pawn shop. That said, if your not some wanna be barter king or american picker looking to get rich off me I have a couple nice guns for sale and maybe trade.

 First up is my American Classic Commander. This gun came out of the box as one of my favorite 1911s. No it's no kimber but but it's every bit as tight and accurate as it's high dollar counter parts. It came factory with almost all the bells and whistles and I filled in the blanks after that. Please take a moment to do a google search and see all the features this pistol comes with straight from the factory. On top of that I have hand polished all the internals not with a dremmel but hand polished all the internals to no more than -.040 off the factory original finish for a smooth as glass trigger and nearly no felt guide rod spring travel, as well as a smooth return for the follow up that the highest priced 1911 will be envious of. I finished the exterior of this sturdy pistol with Brownells Teflon/Molly Gunkote for a long lasting lube free corrosion proof finish that will last well past your grandchildren and all they can throw at it.  And I didn't stop there. This classic hand cannon sports Houge grip panels and a Pearce wrap around grip for the best possible positive grip on a 1911 you can get while maintaining the classic look that should accompany a 1911. Also installed is the hand polished Ed Brown two piece guide rod for a guaranteed no bind spring carrier as well as some added muzzle weight to help with those split second follow up shots whether it be on the competition range or that shady spot you thought you would never be in. This gun handles like a dream and hits like a nightmare.  And looks pretty cool either way (I'd hate for my adversary to die looking down the barrel of a thug wheeling a glock, everyone has to die, might as well give them the class they didn't afford you) .   I can also include some quality brass cased re loadable ammo for average store shelf price, I'm by no means dieing to let go of my ammo, in most cases I'll have to die to give up my ammo, but theres something out there I really want to feel the recoil from. It,the 1911, will come in the factory case with one magazine and the factory guide rod and spring retainer. And just in case you couldn't tell by the pictures this isn't some cobbled up shade tree job with painted sites and a home cut barrel. This has been hand crafted by a pro not some shade tree so low ballers will be ignored.

 Next up is my used off the shelf Taurus Circuit Judge. Like I said it's a used off the shelf gun nothing all that special, but a ton of fun to shoot. These aren't available with a "Taurus" stamp any longer but thats about all that sets it apart from the rest on the firing line. Maybe in twenty years that might mean something but for now I enjoy shooting it so as mentioned earlier I'm not looking to give it away. If we can make terms it will include both choke tubes it came with as well as the optic rail and lock key.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mauser 98 Sporter
postcontent: Up for sale/trade is a Well executed Mauser 98 sporter. It is chambered in 8mm Mauser-if you know anything about the 8mm, it's a hard hitter. The European equivalent of the venerable 06, but pushing a .32 caliber, 196 grain pill. I have been told that this rifle is an interwar British, German, or Belgian rework of a military action. No matter the origins, it is well done. Bluing strog throughout. Only rust present is under the barrel sling swivel. I don't believe it's the barrel itself, rather the solder from the swivel. It shows signs of honest use, but not abuse (scratches in varnish). I will also include an extra wood stock. The action fits the stock, but the pronghorn magazine floor plate/trigger guard does not.
